@GiudGiud the NoBCBC just weakly adds the stresses on the boundaries, so it's basically setting: stress = stress ... so it's doing nothing. Practically speaking it imposes some condition on some higher derivative. Here's what's in our documentation:

The INSADMomentumNoBCBC class is used to implement the "No Boundary Condition" developed by Griffiths. According to Griffiths, the "No Boundary Condition" is equivalent to imposing the condition on the original analytical problem that the (p+1)st derivative of a finite element variable of order p should vanish at a point close to the outflow. This is claimed to reduce error relative to a natural boundary condition.

